INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2a9f203e-d919-4824-85c4-ae71c97cd9e3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$dbt + Spark — Model Types, Tests, and Lineage with the dbt-spark Adapter$escape$,
  $escape$dbt-spark exposes four materializations, each with Spark-specific behavior. `view` creates a Spark SQL view — cheap but recomputed on every query. `table` runs a full `CREATE TABLE AS SELECT` using your configured `file_format` (parquet, delta, iceberg). `incremental` is where Spark diverges: with Delta Lake, set `incremental_strategy='merge'` and a `unique_key`; without it, fall back to `insert_overwrite` on `partition_by` columns — dbt rewrites only touched partitions. `snapshot` uses `dbt_valid_from`/`dbt_valid_to` SCD Type 2 logic, stored as a Delta table for time-travel support.

Tests live in schema.yml — `not_null`, `unique`, `accepted_values`, `relationships`. Add `dbt test --select +my_model` to run upstream tests too. Macros are Jinja2 functions: use `{{ ref('model') }}` to wire lineage (dbt builds the DAG from these calls) and `{{ source('schema', 'table') }}` to track raw ingestion tables. Run `dbt docs generate && dbt docs serve` to visualize the full Spark pipeline graph, including column-level lineage with dbt 1.6+ and a supported metadata adapter.$escape$,
  $escape$-- models/events_incremental.sql
{{ config(
    materialized='incremental',
    file_format='delta',
    incremental_strategy='merge',
    unique_key='event_id',
    partition_by=['event_date']
) }}

SELECT
    event_id,
    user_id,
    cast(event_ts AS DATE) AS event_date,
    event_ts
FROM {{ source('raw', 'events') }}
{% if is_incremental() %}
WHERE event_ts > (SELECT MAX(event_ts) FROM {{ this }})
{% endif %}$escape$,
  $escape$sql$escape$,
